ljs@cs.brown.edu writes in article <LJS.94Mar1130747@gano.cs.brown.edu>:
 
> One further question: Ms. Denning's article says that: "...my security
> device will negotiate a session key K with the device at the other end
> (in general, any method of key exchange can be used)."  If all the FBI
> (or anyone else) needs to decrypt the session is the session key K,
> then doesn't it become *VERY* important how the session key K is
> negotiated? Presumably the FBI has access to the part of the session
> where the session key is negotiated.  If it's negotiated with ROT13
> then the entire session is decryptable real-time, without a warrant,
> if you know the SkipJack algorithm.  I suppose that's why Skipjack is
> classified.

If SkipJack is as good an algorithm as it is puported to be, then it
need not be, and indeed *shouldn't* be classified.  A strong algorithm is
one in which does *not* depend on one's attacker not knowing the
algorithm.  If Skipjack was made public we could sit here all day debating
it's relative strengths & weaknesses instead of wasting our time on DS.


Very sophisticated means of negotiating session keys are available.
The easiest to understand is one based on public key cryptography:

(from Applied Cryptography by Bruce Schneier)

Bob sends Alice his public key.*
Alice generates a random session key, k, encrypts it using Bob's public key,
and sends it to Bob.
Bob then decrypts Alice's message using his private key.
Both of them encrypt their communications using the same session key.

* and we all remember that your public key is just that - public - sending it
in the clear doesn't compromise the security of the system

(substitute your favourite clipper chips for bob and alice ... )

>         Could someone out there please stop throwing flames at Dave
